title: Greater_than
markdown:
# Greater than (>)

 The **greater than (`>`)** operator returns `true` if the left operand is greater than the right operand, and `false` otherwise.

## [Try it](#try%5Fit)

## [Syntax](#syntax)

```
x > y

```

## [Description](#description)

The operands are compared using the same algorithm as the [Less than](/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Less%5Fthan) operator, except the two operands are swapped. `x > y` is generally equivalent to `y < x`, except that `x > y` coerces `x` to a primitive before `y`, while `y < x` coerces `y` to a primitive before `x`. Because coercion may have side effects, the order of the operands may matter.

## [Examples](#examples)

### [String to string comparison](#string%5Fto%5Fstring%5Fcomparison)

```
"a" > "b"; // false
"a" > "a"; // false
"a" > "3"; // true

```

### [String to number comparison](#string%5Fto%5Fnumber%5Fcomparison)

```
"5" > 3; // true
"3" > 3; // false
"3" > 5; // false

"hello" > 5; // false
5 > "hello"; // false

"5" > 3n; // true
"3" > 5n; // false

```

### [Number to Number comparison](#number%5Fto%5Fnumber%5Fcomparison)

```
5 > 3; // true
3 > 3; // false
3 > 5; // false

```

### [Number to BigInt comparison](#number%5Fto%5Fbigint%5Fcomparison)

```
5n > 3; // true
3 > 5n; // false

```

### [Comparing Boolean, null, undefined, NaN](#comparing%5Fboolean%5Fnull%5Fundefined%5Fnan)

```
true > false; // true
false > true; // false

true > 0; // true
true > 1; // false

null > 0; // false
1 > null; // true

undefined > 3; // false
3 > undefined; // false

3 > NaN; // false
NaN > 3; // false

```
